   "source": [
    "# Polynomial cardinal functions\n",
    "\n",
    "In {doc}`interp-global` and {doc}`interp-pwise` we saw a big difference between polynomial interpolation and piecewise polynomial interpolation of some arbitrarily chosen data. The same effects can be seen clearly in the cardinal functions."
   ]

   "source": [
    "using FundamentalsNumericalComputation\n",
    "\n",
    "plot!(FNC.spinterp(t,y),-1,1,label=\"spline\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"x\",ylabel=\"p(x)\",title=\"Piecewise cubic cardinal function\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The piecewise cubic cardinal function is nowhere greater than one in absolute value. This happens to be true for all the cardinal functions, ensuring a good condition number for the interpolation. But the story for global polynomials is very different."
   ]
  },
